n| image               = [[File:The Spectrum Philadelphia PA.jpg|300px|Wachovia Spectrum]]\n| address             = 3601 South Broad Street\n| location            = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| coordinates         = {{Coord|39|54|15|N|75|10|16|W|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-PA|display=it}}\n| broke_ground        = June 1, 1966<ref name=\"groundbreaking\">{{cite news |title=Snider-Wolman Feud Outliving Spectrum|first=Stan|last=Hochman|url=http://articles.philly.com/2009-03-17/sports/24998008_1_ed-snider-spectrum-training-camp|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=March 17, 2009|accessdate=April 25, 2012}}</ref>\n| opened              = September 30, 1967\n| closed              = October 31, 2009\n| demolished          = November 23, 2010 - May 2011\n| renovated           = 1986\n| owner               = [[Comcast Spectacor|Comcast Spectacor, L.P.]]\n| operator            = [[Comcast Spectacor#Global Spectrum|Global Spectrum]]\n| surface             = Multi-surface\n| construction_cost   = \n| architect           = [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]]\n| general_contractor  = [[Thomas McCloskey|McCloskey & Company, Inc.]]\n| former_names        = {{ubl|Spectrum (1967\u20131994)|CoreStates Spectrum (1994\u20131998)|First Union Spectrum (1998\u20132003)|Wachovia Spectrum (2003\u20132009)}}\n| seating_capacity    = Concerts:<br>*End stage: 18,369<br>*Center stage: 19,456<br>*Theater: 5,000\u20138,000<br/>Basketball: 18,168<br/>Ice Hockey: 17,380\n| tenants             = [[Philadelphia Flyers]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1967\u20131996)<br/>[[Philadelphia 76ers]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1967\u20131996)<br/>[[Philadelphia Freedoms (1974)|Philadelphia Freedoms]] ([[World Team Tennis|WTT]]) (1974)<br/>[[Philadelphia Wings (1974\u201375)|Philadelphia Wings]] ([[National Lacrosse League (1974\u20131975)|NLL]]) (1974\u20131975)<br/>[[Philadelphia Fever]] ([[Major Indoor Soccer League (1978-1992)|MISL]]) (1978\u20131981)<br>[[Philadelphia Wings (1987\u20132014)|Philadelphia Wings]] ([[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]) (1987\u20131996)<br/>[[Philadelphia Bulldogs]] ([[Roller Hockey International|RHI]]) (1994\u20131996)<br/>[[Philadelphia Phantoms]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (1996\u20132009)<br/>[[Philadelphia KiXX]] ([[National Professional Soccer League (1984\u20132001)|NPSL]]/[[Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008)|MISL]]/[[National Indoor Soccer League|NISL]]) (1996\u20132009)<br/>[[La Salle Explorers]] ([[NCAA]]) (1996&ndash;1998)<br />[[Philadelphia Soul]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (2004\u20132008) (select games)\n}}\n\nThe '''Spectrum''' (later known as '''CoreStates Spectrum''', '''First Union Spectrum''' and '''Wachovia Spectrum''') was an [[indoor arena]] in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]. Opened in the fall of 1967 as part of what is now known as the [[South Philadelphia Sports Complex]], after several expansions of its [[seating capacity]] it accommodated 18,168 for [[basketball]] and 17,380 for [[ice hockey]], [[arena football]], [[indoor soccer]], and [[box lacrosse]].\n\nThe last event at the Spectrum was a [[Pearl Jam]] concert on October 31, 2009. The arena was demolished between November 2010 and May 2011.\n\n==History==\nOpened as the Spectrum in fall 1967, Philadelphia's first modern indoor sports [[arena]] was built to be the home of the expansion [[Philadelphia Flyers]] of the [[National Hockey League|NHL]], and also to accommodate the existing [[Philadelphia 76ers]] of the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]. The building was the second major sports facility built at the south end of [[Broad Street (Philadelphia)|Broad Street]] in an area previously known as East League Island Park and now referred to simply as the [[South Philadelphia Sports Complex]].\n\n===Early years===\nGround was broken on the arena on June 1, 1966, by [[Jerry Wolman]] and then-Philadelphia Mayor [[James Hugh Joseph Tate|James Tate]] as the home of the NHL's expansion [[Philadelphia Flyers]].<ref name=\"groundbreaking\" /> The first event at the arena was the Quaker City Jazz Festival on September 30, 1967,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bulls game at Wachovia Spectrum highlights Sixers 2008-09 schedule|publisher=[[Philadelphia 76ers]]|url=http://www.nba.com/sixers/news/schedule_080806.html|accessdate=August 15, 2008}}</ref> produced by Larry Magid.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Klein |title=Inqlings: Spectrum Last Blasts: Deafening, of Course |date=September 15, 2008 |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |url=http://www.philly.com/inquirer/columnists/michael_klein/20080918_Inqlings__Spectrum_last_blasts__Deafening__of_course.html |accessdate=October 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023230911/http://www.philly.com/inquirer/columnists/michael_klein/20080918_Inqlings__Spectrum_last_blasts__Deafening__of_course.html |archivedate=October 23, 2008 }}</ref> The first sporting event at the arena was an October 17, 1967 boxing match featuring [[Joe Frazier]] vs. Tony Doyle.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Spectrum|publisher=phillyboxinghistory.com|url=http://www.phillyboxinghistory.com/venues/venue_spectrum.htm|accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref> From 1967 through 1972, fifteen fight cards were held at the Spectrum. The NBA's 76ers also moved there from [[Philadelphia Civic Center|Convention Hall]] as a second major league sports tenant. Lou Scheinfeld, former President of the Spectrum, explained that the name \"Spectrum\" was selected to evoke the broad range of events to be held there. \"The 'SP' for 'sports' and 'South Philadelphia,' 'E' for 'entertainment,' 'C' for 'circuses,' 'T' for 'theatricals,' 'R' for 'recreation,' and 'UM' as 'um, what a nice building!\"  Scheinfeld also said that a seat in the city's first superbox initially cost $1,000 a year: \"For every Flyers game, Sixers game, circus, you name it, you got 250 events for $1,000.\"<ref>October 19, 2009, Talk Philly, CBS3.</ref> The Flyers won their first ever home game in this arena by defeating the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]], 1\u20130. [[Bill Sutherland]] scored the arena's first goal.\n\nOn March 1, 1968, wind blew part of the covering off the Spectrum's roof during a performance of the [[Ice Capades]], forcing the building to close for a month while Mayor Tate fought with then-Philadelphia County District Attorney [[Arlen Specter]] over responsibility for the construction of the roof, and the damage was repaired.<ref>{{cite news |first=William|last=Johnson|title=A Heavy Blow In A Windy City|date=April 1, 1968|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1081004/1/index.htm|accessdate=March 18, 2009}}</ref> The 76ers moved their home games to Convention Hall and to the [[Palestra]], but neither of those arenas had ice rinks at the time, and there were no other NHL-quality sites in the Philadelphia area. Thus the Flyers hurriedly moved their next home game (against the [[Oakland Seals]]) to [[Madison Square Garden]] in [[New York City|New York]] followed by a meeting with the [[Boston Bruins]] played at [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] in [[Toronto]] before establishing a base at [[Colis\u00e9e de Qu\u00e9bec|Le Colis\u00e9e]] in [[Quebec City]], home of their top minor league team, the [[American Hockey League|AHL]] [[Quebec Aces]], for the remainder of their regular season, marking the first NHL games in Quebec City in over four decades, and years before the [[Quebec Nordiques]] joined the NHL. (The roof was repaired in time to permit the Flyers to return to the Spectrum to open their first [[Stanley Cup]] playoffs against the [[St. Louis Blues]] on April 4, 1968; the opening faceoff came just as [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] was [[Assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr.|assassinated]] in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]].)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=434641|title=This Date In Flyers History&nbsp;... March 1|date=March 1, 2005|accessdate=December 20, 2012|publisher=PhiladelphiaFlyers.com}}</ref> Similarly, in 1993, the Flyers played a day game against the Los Angeles Kings during a blizzard. A piece of flying debris smashed out one of the concourse windows, cancelling the game just after the first period.\n\nIn the 1970s, the venue's location on Broad Street and the reputation for [[Bare-knuckle boxing|fisticuffs]] that the Flyers had developed led to the nickname \"Broad Street Bullies.\"\n\nA plaque inside The Spectrum stated that it held the world record for the fastest conversion from Hockey to Basketball.\n\nThe Spectrum, along with the [[Met Center]] and [[The Forum (Inglewood, California)|The Forum]], was one of the first sports arenas to have a scoreboard with a messageboard. Furthermore, the messageboards on the Spectrum scoreboard were the first dot matrix screens in pro hockey or basketball, capable of photos, animation, and replays as well as messages. This was replaced in 1986 with ArenaVision, which consisted of six {{convert|9|by|12|foot|adj=on}} [[rear-projection television|rear-projection videoscreens]] at the top and a four-sided American Sign and Indicator scoreboard at the bottom. Inside the videoscreens were [[General Electric]] projectors located {{convert|15|ft}} away from each screen.<ref>[http://articles.philly.com/1986-09-16/sports/26072413_1_new-scoreboard-clear-picture-spectrum Juliano, Joe \"Spectrum to Unveil New Scoreboard,\" ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', September 16, 1986]</ref>\n\n===Seating capacity===\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Basketball\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Philadelphia 76ers}}\"|Years\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell|Philadelphia 76ers}}\"|Capacity\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Philadelphia 76ers}}\"|1967\u20131971\n| 15,244<ref>{{cite news |title=Bucks Trounce 76ers, 156-120, on Record Playoff Score and Lead Series, 2-1|first=George|last=Vecsey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/03/31/archives/bucks-trounce-76ers-156120-on-record-playoff-score-and-lead-series.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 31, 1970|accessdate=February 25, 2013|page=45}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Philadelphia 76ers}}\"|1971\u20131972\n| 15,304<ref>{{cite news |title=Ailing Bulls Wallop 76ers 116-99|first=Bob|last=Logan|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/614249742.html?dids=614249742:614249742&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Mar+25%2C+1972&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Ailing+Bulls+Wallop+76ers+116-99&pqatl=google|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=March 25, 1972|accessdate=February 25, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Philadelphia 76ers}}\"|1972\u20131973\n| <div style=\"text-align: center;\">17,300</div>\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Philadelphia 76ers}}\"|1973\u20131981\n| 18,276<ref>{{cite news |title=Dawkins Keys Sixers|first=Doyle|last=Dietz|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TTQxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sKIFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5174,1704604&dq=en|newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]]|date=May 12, 1980|accessdate=February 25, 2013|page=20}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Philadelphia 76ers}}\"|1981\u20131982\n| 18,364<ref>{{cite news |title=Sixers Finally Lose to Hawks, 106-99|first=George|last=Shirk|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB29362EFD44EFF&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=November 7, 1981|accessdate=February 25, 2013|page=C01}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"{{NBA color cell2|Philadelphia 76ers}}\"|1982\u20131985\n| 17,921<ref>{{cite news |title=Sixers Ring in Season|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DN&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI%7CDN&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB295DE28BB7B15&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=Go