egory:Philadelphia Flyers arenas]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia 76ers venues]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phantoms]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:La Salle Explorers men's basketball]]\n[[Category:Demolished sports venues in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1967]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1967]]\n[[Category:1967 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:2009 disestablishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Culture of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Defunct boxing venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:South Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:2011 disestablishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sports venues demolished in 2011]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor lacrosse venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Bulldogs]]\n[[Category:Defunct indoor arenas in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Villanova Wildcats men's basketball]]\n[[Category:NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament Final Four venues]]\n", "name_user": "Sk8erboi97", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable concerts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrum_(arena)"}
{"title_page": "Ant social networks", "text_new": "The social network of colonies of social insects have been extensively studied as model biological networks.\n\n===Social contact networks===\n====Information transfer====\n\n===Trophallaxis networks===\n\nThe network of [[trophallaxis]] events differs from the network of social contacts. In the trophallaxis network of [[Lasius niger]], foragers have higher betweenness and centrality than domestic workers, and the domestic workers appear to form three clusters.\n\n===Disease transmission===\nThe social network can dynamically respond to the presence of pathogens in a way which reduces transmission.\n", "text_old": "===Social contact networks===\n====Information transfer====\n\n===Trophallaxis networks===\n\nThe network of [[trophallaxis]] events differs from the network of social contacts. In the trophallaxis network of [[Lasius niger]], foragers have higher betweenness and centrality than domestic workers, and the domestic workers appear to form three clusters.\n\n===Disease transmission===\nThe social network can dynamically respond to the presence of pathogens in a way which reduces transmission.\n", "name_user": "Tomahawk Tasmania", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant_social_networks"}
{"title_page": "Heherson Alvarez", "text_new": "{{short description|Filipino politician}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| honorific_suffix    = \n| name                = Heherson T. Alvarez\n| image               = File:Senator Heherson Alvarez.jpg|\n| order               = \n| office1             = Commissioner of the Climate Change Commission\n| term_start1         = October 23, 2009\n| term_end1           = June 30, 2016\n| predecessor1        = \n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources|Secretary of Environment and Natural Resources]]\n| term_start2         = March 29, 2001\n| term_end2           = December 13, 2002\n| predecessor2        = [[Antonio Cerilles]]\n| successor2          = Elisea G. Gozun\n| office3             = Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] from [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]]'s [[Legislative districts of Isabela#4th District|4th District]]\n| term_start3         = June 30, 1998\n| term_end3           = June 30, 2001\n| predecessor3        = Antonio M. Abaya\n| successor3          = Antonio M. Abaya\n| office4             = [[Senator of the Philippines]]\n| term_start4         = June 30, 1987\n| term_end4           = June 30, 1998\n| office5             = [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]]\n| term_start5         = February 7, 1987\n| term_end5           = March 7, 1987\n| predecessor5        = ''Post Created''\n| successor5          = Vacant<ref>vacant after his resignation</ref><small>Post later held by Philip E. Juico</Small>\n| office6             = [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Minister of Agrarian Reform]]\n| term_start6         = May 1, 1986\n| term_end6           = February 7, 1987\n| predecessor6        = [[Conrado F. Estrella]]\n| successor6          = ''Post Abolished''\n| birth_name          = Heherson Turingan Alvarez\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1939|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Santiago, Isabela]], [[Commonwealth of the Philippines]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|4|20|1939|10|16|df=y}}\n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = [[Philippines|Filipino]]\n| party               = [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP-Laban]] (1986\u20131988); (2018\u20132020)\n| otherparty          = [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|LDP]] (1988\u20131998); (2004\u20132018), [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|LDP]]-[[Agapito Aquino|Aquino]] Wing (2004), [[Lakas\u2013CMD (1991)|Lakas NUCD-UMDP]] (1998\u20132001)\n| spouse              = Cecile Guidote\n| relations           = \n| children            = 2\n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Harvard University]], [[University of the Philippines]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = [[Politician]]\n| signature           = \n| website             = http://www.hehersonalvarez.com/\n}}\n\n'''Heherson''' \"'''Sonny'''\" '''Turingan Alvarez''' (October 16, 1939 \u2013 April 20, 2020) was a politician from the Philippines. He served as a member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]] and the [[Senate of the Philippines]]. He also was [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]], and [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Minister of Agrarian Reform]].\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Heherson Alvarez.jpg|280px|thumb|right|Alvarez speaking at a forum in Manila Hotel]]\n[[File:President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo shakes hands with Mayor of Libacao, Aklan Charito Navarosa.jpg|280px|thumb|right|Heherson Alvarez shown with the President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]]\nSonny Alvarez studied liberal arts at University of the Philippines. He also earned a master's degree in Economics and Public Administration from [[Harvard University]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAlvarez married Cecile Guidote; the couple had two children, Hexilon and Xilca.\n\n==Death==\nOn April 20, 2020, Alvarez died due to complications from [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1261695/ex-senator-heherson-alvarez-succumbs-to-covid-19|title=Ex-Senator Heherson Alvarez succumbs to COVID-19|last=Galvez|first=Daphne|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{navboxes\n|title=Senatorial history of Heherson Alvarez\n|list=\n{{8th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{9th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{10th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alvarez, Heherson}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino politicians]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 10th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 9th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 8th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives of the Philippines from Isabela (province)]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago (Philippine city)]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Agrarian Reform of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Environment and Natural Resources of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Filipino expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corazon Aquino Administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n\n\n{{Philippines-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Filipino politician}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| honorific_suffix    = \n| name                = Heherson T. Alvarez\n| image               = File:Senator Heherson Alvarez.jpg|\n| order               = \n| office1             = Commissioner of the Climate Change Commission\n| term_start1         = October 23, 2009\n| term_end1           = June 30, 2016\n| predecessor1        = \n| successor1          = \n| office2             = [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources|Secretary of Environment and Natural Resources]]\n| term_start2         = March 29, 2001\n| term_end2           = December 13, 2002\n| predecessor2        = [[Antonio Cerilles]]\n| successor2          = Elisea G. Gozun\n| office3             = Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] from [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]]'s [[Legislative districts of Isabela#4th District|4th District]]\n| term_start3         = June 30, 1998\n| term_end3           = June 30, 2001\n| predecessor3        = Antonio M. Abaya\n| successor3          = Antonio M. Abaya\n| office4             = [[Senator of the Philippines]]\n| term_start4         = June 30, 1987\n| term_end4           = June 30, 1998\n| office5             = [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]]\n| term_start5         = February 7, 1987\n| term_end5           = March 7, 1987\n| predecessor5        = ''Post Created''\n| successor5          = Vacant<ref>vacant after his resignation</ref><small>Post later held by Philip E. Juico</Small>\n| office6             = [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Minister of Agrarian Reform]]\n| term_start6         = May 1, 1986\n| term_end6           = February 7, 1987\n| predecessor6        = [[Conrado F. Estrella]]\n| successor6          = ''Post Abolished''\n| birth_name          = Heherson Turingan Alvarez\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1939|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Santiago, Isabela]], [[Commonwealth of the Philippines]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|4|20|1939|10|16|df=y}}\n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = [[Philippines|Filipino]]\n| party               = [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP-Laban]] (1986\u20131988); (2018\u20132020)\n| otherparty          = [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|LDP]] (1988\u20131998); (2004\u20132018), [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|LDP]]-[[Agapito Aquino|Aquino]] Wing (2004), [[Lakas\u2013CMD (1991)|Lakas NUCD-UMDP]] (1998\u20132001)\n| spouse              = Cecile Guidote\n| relations           = \n| children            = 2\n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Harvard University]], [[University of the Philippines]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = [[Politician]]\n| signature           = \n| website             = http://www.hehersonalvarez.com/\n}}\n\n'''Heherson''' \"'''Sonny'''\" '''Turingan Alvarez''' (October 16, 1939 \u2013 April 20, 2020) was a politician from the Philippines. He served as a member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]] and the [[Senate of the Philippines]]. He also was [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]], and [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Minister of Agrarian Reform]].\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Heherson Alvarez.jpg|280px|thumb|right|Alvarez speaking at a forum in Manila Hotel]]\n[[File:President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo shakes hands with Mayor of Libacao, Aklan Charito Navarosa.jpg|280px|thumb|right|Heherson Alvarez shown with the President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]]\nSonny Alvarez studied liberal arts at University of the Philippines. He also earned a master's degree in Economics and Public Administration from [[Harvard University]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAlvarez married Cecile Guidote; the couple had two children, Hexilon and Xilca.\n\n==Death==\nOn April 20th, 2020, Alvarez died due to complications from [[coronavirus disease 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1261695/ex-senator-heherson-alvarez-succumbs-to-covid-19|title=Ex-Senator Heherson Alvarez succumbs to COVID-19|last=Galvez|first=Daphne|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{navboxes\n|title=Senatorial history of Heherson Alvarez\n|list=\n{{8th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{9th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{10th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alvarez, Heherson}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Filipino environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino politicians]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 10th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 9th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 8th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives of the Philippines from Isabela (province)]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago (Philippine city)]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Agrarian Reform of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Environment and Natural Resources of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Filipino expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corazon Aquino Administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n\n\n{{Philippines-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CAWylie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heherson_Alvarez"}
{"title_page": "Major League Baseball", "text_new": "{{short description|Professional baseball league}}\n{{Redirect|MLB|Minor League Baseball|Minor League Baseball|other uses|MLB (disambiguation)}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| upcoming_season = 2020 Major League Baseball season\n| logo = Major League Baseball logo.svg\n| sport = Baseball\n| founded = {{start date and age|1903}}<ref>{{cite web|title=The Commissionership: A Historical Perspective|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/mlb_history_people.jsp?story=com|publisher=[[MLB Advanced Media]]|website=[[MLB.com]]|access-date=March 11, 2016|quote=The strength of the American League grew as an increasing number of National League players opted for the higher salaries offered by the new association. Faced with the prospect of losing many of its best players, the NL chose peace and declared the AL its equal in 1903. This led to a new National Agreement and the birth of the World Series. The American and National Leagues were established as major leagues and all other associations comprised the minor leagues, which fell under the jurisdiction of the National Association of Professional Baseball Leagues.}}</ref><br />([[National League]], 1876)<ref name=noble/><br />([[American League]], 1901)<ref name=noble/>\n| commissioner = [[Rob Manfred]]<ref name=\"manfred\">{{cite news|title=MLB Executives|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/about_mlb/executives.jsp?bio=manfred_rob|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|website=MLB.com|access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> \n| teams = [[Current Major League Baseball franchises|30]]<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web|title=MLB Team Contact Information|url=https://www.mlb.com/team|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|website=MLB.com|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| champion = [[Washington Nationals]]<br />(1st title)\n| most_champs = [[New York Yankees]]<br />(27 titles)<ref>{{cite web|title=World Series History: Championships by Club|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/postseason/mlb_ws.jsp?feature=club_champs|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|website=MLB.com|access-date=March 11, 2016}}</ref>\n| countries = United States (29 teams)<br />Canada (1 team)\n| headquarters = [[1271 Avenue of the Americas]]<ref>{{Cite web| title = Major League Baseball 1271 Sixth Avenue {{!}} Rockefeller Group| work = The Real Deal New York| accessdate = 2020-01-08| date = 2017-11-16| url = https://therealdeal.com/2017/11/16/major-league-baseball-gives-back-75k-sf-on-sixth-avenue/}}</ref><br>[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States\n| TV = {{unbulleted list\n| '''United States:'''\n| [[ESPN Major League Baseball|ESPN/ESPN2]]\n| [[Fox Major League Baseball|Fox/FS1]]\n| [[Major League Baseball on TBS|TBS]]\n| [[MLB Network]]\n| [[YouTube]] (live streaming)<ref>{{cite web|title=National Broadcast Schedule|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/broadcasts/national.jsp?tcid=mm_mlb_schedule|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|website=MLB.com|access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MLB Game of the Week Live on YouTube|url=https://www.mlb.com/live-stream-games/youtube|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|website=MLB.com|access-date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| '''Canada:'''\n| [[Sportsnet]]\n| [[R\u00e9seau des sports|RDS]]\n| [[TVA Sports]]\n| [[The Sports Network|TSN/TSN2]]\n| [[MLB Network]] \n}}\n| website = {{url|http://mlb.com}}\n}}\n'''Major League Baseball''' ('''MLB''') is a [[professional baseball]] organization. It is the oldest of the [[major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada]]. A total of 30 teams play in Major League Baseball: 15 teams in the [[National League]] (NL) and 15 in the [[American League]] (AL). The NL and AL were formed as separate legal entities in 1876 and 1901, respectively. Beginning in 1903, the two leagues cooperated but remained legally separate entities. In 2000 the leagues merged into a single organization led by the [[Commissioner of Baseball]].<ref name=2000nl>{{cite web|title=Year In Review: 2000 National League|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/yearly/yr2000n.shtml|website=Baseball-Almanac.com|accessdate=September 5, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Chass|first=Murray|title=BASEBALL; League Presidents Out As Baseball Centralizes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/09/16/sports/baseball-league-presidents-out-as-baseball-centralizes.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 16, 1999|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMLB also oversees [[Minor League Baseball]], which comprises 256 teams affiliated with the major league clubs. MLB and the [[World Baseball Softball Confederation]] jointly manage the international [[World Baseball Classic]] tournament.\n\nBaseball's first openly all-professional team was the Cincinnati Red Stockings founded in 1869. Before that, some teams had [[secret]]ly paid some players. The first few decades of professional baseball were characterized by rivalries between leagues and by players who often jumped from one team or league to another.\n\nThe period before 1920 is known as the [[dead-ball era]], during which players would rarely hit [[home run]]s. Professional baseball in the [[United States]] survived a conspiracy to [[match fixing|fix]] the [[1919 World Series]], which came to be known as the [[Black Sox Scandal]]. The sport rose in popularity in the 1920s, and survived potential downturns during the [[Great Depression]] and World War II. Shortly after the war, [[Jackie Robinson]] broke [[baseball color line|baseball's color barrier]].\n\nThe 1950s and 1960s were a time of expansion for the AL and NL, then new stadiums and artificial turf surfaces began to change the game in the 1970s and 1980s. Home runs dominated the game during the 1990s, and media reports began to discuss the use of [[anabolic steroid]]s among MLB players in the mid-2000s. In 2006, an investigation produced the [[Mitchell Report]], which implicated many players in the use of [[performance-enhancing drugs|performance-enhancing substances]], including at least one player from each team.\n\nToday, MLB is composed of [[Current Major League Baseball franchises|30 teams]]: 29 in the United States and 1 in Canada. Teams play 162 games each season and 5 teams in each league advance to a four-round [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason tournament]] that culminates in the [[World Series]], a [[best-of-seven playoff|best-of-seven]] championship series between the two league champions that dates to 1903. Baseball broadcasts are aired on television, radio, and the Internet throughout North America and in several other countries. MLB has the [[List of attendance figures at domestic professional sports leagues|highest season attendance]] of any sports league in the world with more than 69.6&nbsp;million spectators in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maurybrown/2018/10/03/how-mlb-attendance-dropped-below-70-million-for-first-time-in-15-years/#7b44d74d61bf|title=Why MLB Attendance Dropped Below 70 Million For The First Time In 15 Years|last1=Brown|first1=Maury|date=October 3, 2018|website=Forbes.com|publisher=Forbes|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|accessdate=April 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Organizational structure==\nMLB is governed by the [[Major League Baseball Constitution]]. This document has undergone several incarnations since its creation in 1876.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Berg|first1=Ted|title=Someone is selling MLB's original 1876 constitution, and it's expected to fetch millions|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2017/04/mlb-original-constitution-national-league-base-ball-sale-auction|website=USAToday.com|accessdate=August 22, 2017|date=April 21, 2017}}</ref> Under the direction of the [[Commissioner of Baseball]], MLB hires and maintains the sport's [[umpire (baseball)|umpiring]] crews, and negotiates marketing, labor, and [[Major League Baseball television contracts|television contracts]]. MLB maintains a unique, controlling relationship over the sport, including most aspects of [[Minor League Baseball]]. This is due in large part to the 1922 [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] ruling in ''[[Federal Baseball Club v. National League]]'', which held that baseball is not [[Commerce Clause|interstate commerce]] and therefore not subject to federal [[antitrust]] law. This ruling has been weakened only slightly in subsequent years.<ref name=\"Policy Debate: Should the antitrust exemption for baseball be eliminated?\" /> The weakened ruling granted more stability to the owners of teams and has resulted in values increasing at double-digit rates.<ref name=\"Policy Debate: Should the antitrust exemption for baseball be eliminated?\">{{cite web|url=http://www.swlearning.com/economics/policy_debates/baseball.html|title=Policy Debate: Should the antitrust exemption for baseball be eliminated?|accessdate=September 4, 2008|publisher=www.swlearning.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thesportjournal.org/article/role-antitrust-laws-professional-sports-industry-financial-perspective|title=The Role of Antitrust Laws in the Professional Sports Industry From a Financial Perspective|accessdate=September 4, 2008|work=Howard Bartee, Jr|publisher=The Sport Journal |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607094652/http://www.thesportjournal.org/article/role-antitrust-laws-professional-sports-industry-financial-perspective|archivedate=June 7, 2008}}</ref> There were several challenges to MLB's primacy in the sport between the 1870s and the [[Federal League]] in 1916; the last attempt at a new major league was the aborted [[Continental League]] in 1960.<ref name=\"Policy Debate: Should the antitrust exemption for baseball be eliminated?\" />\n\nThe chief executive of MLB is the commissioner, currently [[Rob Manfred]]. The [[chief operating officer]] is [[Tony Petitti]]. There are five other executives: president (business and media), chief communications officer, chief legal officer, chief financial officer, and chief baseball officer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/8023312/major-league-baseball-executive-jimmie-lee-solomon-resigns-21-years|title=Manfred promoted; Jimmie Lee Solomon resigns|publisher=ESPN|date=June 7, 2012|accessdate=November 29, 2013}}</ref><ref name=execs>{{cite web|title=MLB Executives|website=[[MLB.com]]|year=2013|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/about_mlb/executives.jsp|accessdate=February 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe multimedia branch of MLB, which is based in [[Manhattan]], is [[Major League Baseball Advanced Media|MLB Advanced Media]]. This branch oversees [[MLB.com]] and each of the 30 teams' websites. Its charter states that MLB Advanced Media holds [[editorial independence]] from the league, but it is under the same ownership group and revenue-sharing plan. MLB Productions is a similarly structured wing of the league, focusing on video and traditional broadcast media. MLB also owns 67 percent of [[MLB Network]], with the other 33 percent split between several cable operators and satellite provider [[DirecTV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/network|title=MLB Network|website=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=October 30, 2013}}</ref> It operates out of studios in [[Secaucus, New Jersey]], and also has editorial independence from the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/network/about/|title=About MLB Network|website=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=October 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==League organization==\nIn 1920, the weak National Commission, which had been created to manage relationships between the two leagues, was replaced with the much more powerful Commissioner of Baseball, who had the power to make decisions for all of professional baseball unilaterally.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Commissionership: A Historical Perspective|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/mlb_history_people.jsp?story=com|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media|website=MLB.com|accessdate=November 30, 2013}}</ref> From 1901 to 1960, the American and National Leagues fielded eight teams apiece.\n\nIn the 1960s, MLB expansion added eight teams, including the first non-U.S. team (the [[Montreal Expos]]). Two teams (the [[Seattle Mariners]] and the [[Toronto Blue Jays]]) were also added in the 1970s. From 1969 through 1993, each league consisted of an East and West Division. In 1993, the National League expanded with two teams, the Florida Marlins and the Colorado Rockies, to even up the number of teams in both leagues.  A third division, the Central Division, was formed in each league in 1994. Until 1996, the two leagues met on the field only during the [[World Series]] and the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]]. Regular-season [[interleague play]] was introduced in 1997.<ref name=Interleague>{{cite news|title=Interleague play ho-hum to some|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HjMfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=388EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2778,783864|accessdate=November 24, 2013|newspaper=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]|date=June 4, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1995 two new franchises, the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] and Tampa Bay Devil Rays (now known as the [[Tampa Bay Rays]]), were awarded by MLB, to begin play in 1998. This addition brought the total number of franchises to 30. In early 1997, MLB decided to assign one new team to each league: Tampa Bay joined the AL and Arizona joined the NL. The original plan was to have an odd number of teams in each league (15 per league, with five in each division), but in order for every team to be able to play daily, this would have required interleague play to be scheduled throughout the entire season. However, it was unclear at the time if interleague play would continue after the 1998 season, as it had to be approved by the players' union. For this and other reasons, it was decided that both leagues should continue to have an even number of teams; one existing club would have to switch leagues. The [[Milwaukee Brewers#1994\u201398: Realignment / \"We're taking this thing National\"|Milwaukee Brewers]] agreed in November 1997 to move from the AL to the NL, thereby making the NL a 16-team league. At the same time, the [[Detroit Tigers]] agreed to move from the AL East to the AL Central (to replace Milwaukee), with the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays joining the AL East.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cincypost.com/sports/1997/brew110697.html|title=Brewers switch leagues, join Reds in NL Central|work=[[The Kentucky Post]] ([[Associated Press]])|publisher=[[E. W. Scripps Company]]|date=November 6, 1997|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050505095313/http://www.cincypost.com/sports/1997/brew110697.html |archive-date= May 5, 2005 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Later, when the [[Houston Astros]] changed ownership prior to the 2013 season, the team moved from the NL Central to the AL West,<ref name=\"ESPN-AstrosSale2011\" /><ref name=\"ESPN-MLBTeams\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/teams|title=ESPN: MLB Baseball Teams|accessdate=October 14, 2013}}</ref> resulting in both leagues having three divisions of five teams each and allowing all teams to have a more balanced schedule.<ref name=\"ESPN-AstrosSale2011\" /> Interleague play is now held throughout the season.<ref name=\"ESPN-AstrosSale2011\">MLB required the Astros to accept this move as a condition of approving their sale to [[Jim Crane]].{{cite news|agency=Associated Press|authorlink=Associated Press|title=Astros' sale finalized; 2 more for playoffs|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=November 17, 2011|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/7246443/houston-astros-sale-approved-mlb|accessdate=November 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000 the AL and NL were dissolved as legal entities, and MLB became a single, overall league ''de jure'', similar to the [[National Football League]] (NFL), [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and [[National Hockey League]] (NHL)\u2014albeit with two components called \"leagues\" instead of \"conferences.\" The same [[Baseball rules|rules]] and [[regulation of sport|regulations]] are used in both leagues, with one exception: the AL operates under the [[designated hitter]] rule, while the NL does not.<ref>{{cite web|title=Designated Hitter Rule|url=http://m.mlb.com/glossary/rules/designated-hitter-rule|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media|website=MLB.com|accessdate=February 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Anderson>{{cite news|last=Adamson|first=Scott|title=Nothing more irritating than playing by one set of rules in one park and a different set in another|url=http://www.independentmail.com/news/2011/jul/01/nothing-more-irritating-playing-one-set-rules-one/|newspaper=[[The Anderson Independent-Mail]]|accessdate=November 24, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203014147/http://www.independentmail.com/news/2011/jul/01/nothing-more-irritating-playing-one-set-rules-one/|archivedate=December 3, 2013}}</ref> This difference in rules between leagues is unique to MLB; the other sports leagues of the U.S. and Canada have one set of rules for all teams.\n\n==Teams==\n{{MLB Labelled Map|float=right}}\n{{GeoGroup}}\n{{clear}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|Division\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|Team\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|City\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|Stadium\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|Capacity\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|Coordinates<!--Required for {{GeoGroup}}-->\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|Founded\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|Joined\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|Ref\n|-\n! style=\"{{Baseball primary style|American League}};\" colspan=\"9\"|{{Baseball secondary link|American League|American League}}\n|-\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\" rowspan=\"5\"|[[American League East|East]]\n|'''[[Baltimore Orioles]]'''\n|[[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]]\n|[[Oriole Park at Camden Yards]]\n| align=center | 45,971\n|{{Coord|39|17|2|N|76|37|18|W|type:landmark|name=Baltimore Orioles}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| 1901*\n|align=center|<ref>{{cite web|title=Oriole Park at Camden Yards|url=http://baltimore.orioles.mlb.com/bal/ballpark/index.jsp|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media, LP|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Boston Red Sox]]'''\n|[[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|[[Fenway Park]]\n| align=center | 37,949\n|{{Coord |42|20|47|N|71|5|51|W|type:landmark|name=Boston Red Sox}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| 1901\n|align=center|<ref>{{cite web|title=Fenway Park|url=http://boston.redsox.mlb.com/bos/ballpark/index.jsp|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media, LP|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[New York Yankees]]''' \n|[[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n|[[Yankee Stadium]]\n| align=center | 49,638\n|{{Coord|40|49|45|N|73|55|35|W|type:landmark|name=New York Yankees}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| 1901*\n|align=center|<ref>{{cite web|title=Yankee Stadium|url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/nyy/ballpark/index.jsp|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media, LP|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Tampa Bay Rays]]''' \n|[[St. Petersburg, Florida]]\n|[[Tropicana Field]]\n| align=center | 31,042\n|{{Coord|27|46|6|N|82|39|12|W|type:landmark|name=Tampa Bay Rays}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| 1998\n|align=center|<ref>{{cite web|title=Tropicana Field|url=http://tampabay.rays.mlb.com/tb/ballpark/index.jsp|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media, LP|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=July 21, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Toronto Blue Jays]]'''\n|[[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n|[[Rogers Centre]]\n| align=center | 49,282\n|{{coord|43|38|29|N|79|23|21|W|type:landmark|name=Toronto Blue Jays}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| 1977\n|align=center|<ref>{{cite web|title=Rogers Centre|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/tor/ballpark/index.jsp|publisher=Major League Baseball Advanced Media, LP|date=July 21, 2015|accessdate=Jul